			<p><a href="http://www.hungrynative.com" >Hungry Native</a> &#8211; Niana-Interesting.  We are by no means Pho experts, and weren&#8217;t aware that the clarity of the broth was hallmark of Pho.  This was the first time we&#8217;ve made it ourselves, and we just followed this recipe.  Good to know!</p>

		</div>
	</div>	<div id="comment-225" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 self-clear p3comment">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ac238442fca2ff40f4783375d9f71634?s=25&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-25 photo' height='25' width='25' />
		
		 		
		<div class="comment-text">
			<p>Niana &#8211; I&#8217;m a bit old school about pho.  I don&#8217;t like to add the condiments to the whole bowl.  It clouds up the broth which is almost sacrilegious since a cook spends hours gently simmering (beef bones) to insure a clear broth.  You will find that most pho eaters will mix the hoisin and the sriracha in a little dipping bowl and dip their meat/noodles.  I like to mix together hoisin, sriracha, and lime/lemon juice for the dipping sauce.  It&#8217;s really good and my broth stays nice and clear.</p>

